With $n = 4$, we have $\Delta x = \frac{1}{4}$ and the partition points 
are $x_0 = 0,\; x_1 = \frac{1}{4},\; x_2 = \frac{1}{2},\; 
x_3 = \frac{3}{4},\; x_4 = 1$.

**(a) Left Riemann sum:** We evaluate $f$ at the left endpoints 
$x_0, x_1, x_2, x_3$:
$$
 L_4 &= f(0)\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} + f(\tfrac{1}{4})\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + f(\tfrac{1}{2})\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + f(\tfrac{3}{4})\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} \\
 &= 0\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} + \tfrac{1}{16}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + \tfrac{1}{4}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + \tfrac{9}{16}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} \\
 &= 0 + \tfrac{1}{64} + \tfrac{1}{16} + \tfrac{9}{64} 
 = \frac{0 + 1 + 4 + 9}{64} = \frac{14}{64} = \frac{7}{32} 
 \approx 0.2188.
$$

**(b) Right Riemann sum:** We evaluate $f$ at the right endpoints 
$x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4$:
$$
 R_4 &= f(\tfrac{1}{4})\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + f(\tfrac{1}{2})\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + f(\tfrac{3}{4})\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + f(1)\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} \\
 &= \tfrac{1}{16}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + \tfrac{1}{4}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + \tfrac{9}{16}\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 + 1\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} \\
 &= \frac{1 + 4 + 9 + 16}{64} = \frac{30}{64} = \frac{15}{32} 
 \approx 0.4688.
$$

The true area lies between $L_4 = 0.2188$ and $R_4 = 0.4688$. 
(Since $f(x) = x^2$ is increasing on $[0,1]$, the left sum 
underestimates and the right sum overestimates.)

With $\Delta x = \frac{1}{4}$, the midpoints are $\bar{x}_1 = \frac{1}{8}$, 
$\bar{x}_2 = \frac{3}{8}$, $\bar{x}_3 = \frac{5}{8}$, 
$\bar{x}_4 = \frac{7}{8}$.
$$
 M_4 &= \left[\left(\tfrac{1}{8}\right)^{\!2} 
 + \left(\tfrac{3}{8}\right)^{\!2} 
 + \left(\tfrac{5}{8}\right)^{\!2} 
 + \left(\tfrac{7}{8}\right)^{\!2}\right]\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} \\
 &= \left[\tfrac{1}{64} + \tfrac{9}{64} + \tfrac{25}{64} 
 + \tfrac{49}{64}\right]\cdot\tfrac{1}{4} 
 = \frac{84}{64}\cdot\frac{1}{4} = \frac{84}{256} 
 = \frac{21}{64} \approx 0.3281.
$$
This is already quite close to the true value of $\frac{1}{3} \approx 
0.3333$—much closer than either $L_4 \approx 0.2188$ or 
$R_4 \approx 0.4688$.
